<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:5pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:5pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"margin-top:8pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
11. Borrowings</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:6pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<a name="_Hlk497206925" id="_Hlk497206925"></a>&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
GP Corp. Note</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:6pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The GP Corp. Note was issued in November 2016 with a maximum
principal balance of $10.8 million and a carrying value of
approximately $3.2 million which approximated its fair
value.&nbsp;&nbsp;In September 2017, in conjunction with the
Separation Agreement, the GP Corp. Note was amended and restated to
reduce the maximum principal balance payable under the note from
$10.8 million to $3.3 million.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:12pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<a name="_Hlk504644199" id="_Hlk504644199"></a>&nbsp;<a name=
"_Hlk504644199" id="_Hlk504644199"></a>&nbsp;<font style=
"font-family:Garamond;">Since the amendment resulted in a
substantial change to the GP Corp. Note, the Company accounted for
the amendment as a debt extinguishment.&nbsp;&nbsp;On the amendment
date, the Company recognized, in other income (expense), a loss on
debt extinguishment of $0.05 million.&nbsp;&nbsp;As part of the
consideration to effect the principal reduction, the Company issued
MAST Capital a warrant to purchase up to 420,000 shares of
restricted common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;On the grant date, the warrants
had an estimated fair value of $0.01 million.</font></p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The GP Corp. Note is held by MAST Capital, matures in November
2026, accrues interest at a variable rate of LIBOR plus 3.0% per
annum and is secured by a profit sharing agreement related to GECM’
s management of GECC.&nbsp;&nbsp; The GP Corp. Note requires
quarterly interest only payments and annual principal payments of
$0.08 million, based on the Company’s fiscal year ending June
30.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The GP Corp. Note is non-recourse to any of the Company’s
operations or net assets not related to GECM’s management services
to GECC.&nbsp;&nbsp;The GP Corp. Note may be prepaid at par value
at any time with prior written notice to the holders of the GP
Corp. Note.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, GP Corp. is required to prepay
the GP Corp. Note upon certain material liquidation
transactions.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Senior and Subordinated Notes</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU20" id=
"_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU20"></a>In March 2018, in
conjunction with the acquisition of an 80.1% interest in CRIC IT
Fort Myers LLC, the Company assumed a senior secured note
(<font style="font-weight:bold;">Senior Note</font>) with a
principal balance of $54.8 million and a subordinated note
(<font style="font-weight:bold;">Subordinated Note</font>) with a
principal balance of $2.7 million at the date of the
acquisition.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Senior Note was recorded at an
estimated fair value of $52.2 million, reflecting a discount of
$2.6 million from the face amount; and the Subordinated Note was
recorded at $5.8 million, reflecting a premium of $3.1
million.&nbsp;&nbsp;The discount and premium will</p>
<p style=
"text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
19</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;" />
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<font style=
"font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
amortize over the life of the notes.&nbsp;&nbsp;Both the Senior
Note and Subordinated Note are non-recourse to the
Company</font><font style=
"font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">,
but are secured by the Property, the rights associated with the
Leases</font><font style=
"font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">,
and the stock owned by the Company in the Property
Owner.</font></p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:3pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The note agreements include negative covenants that restrict the
Property Owner’s business operations to ownership and lease of the
Property, limit additional indebtedness, require maintenance of
insurance and other customary requirements related to the Property.
Events of default include non-payment of amounts when due,
inability to pay indebtedness or material change in the business
operations or financial condition of the Property Owner or the
lease tenant that in the Lender’s reasonable determination would
reasonably be expected to materially impair the value of the
Property, prevent timely repayment of the notes, or performing any
material obligations under the note and related
agreements.&nbsp;&nbsp;The payments under the notes are also
guaranteed on a full and several basis by the non-controlling
interest holder of the Property Owner.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:1pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The Senior Note matures on March 15, 2030, and accrues interest at
a rate of 3.49% per annum, and is secured by a first lien mortgage
on the Property and an Assignment of Leases and
Rents.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Senior Note requires monthly principal and
interest payments through the maturity date, with the last payment
of $18.4 million on March 14, 2030.&nbsp;&nbsp;The principal and
interest due on the Senior Note may be prepaid at the option of the
Borrower, discounting the remaining principal and interest payments
at a rate equal to an applicable premium in excess of a rate
corresponding to the specified U.S. Treasury security over the
remaining average life of the Senior Note.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The following table summarizes the obligations due under the terms
of the Senior Note (in thousands):</p>

"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:5pt;">

<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The Subordinated Note matures on March 15, 2030, and accrues
interest at a rate 15.0% per annum, and is secured by a second lien
mortgage on the Property and an Assignment of Leases and
Rents.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Subordinated Note is a capital appreciation
note, whereby the monthly interest is capitalized to the principal
balance and due at maturity.&nbsp;&nbsp;Accordingly, $16.3 million
payment is due on March 15, 2030. The principal and interest due on
the Subordinate Note may be prepaid at the option of the Borrower,
discounting the remaining principal and interest payments at a rate
equal to an applicable premium in excess of a rate corresponding to
the specified U.S. Treasury security over the remaining average
life of the Subordinated Note.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">

obligations due under the terms of the Subordinated Note (in
thousands):</p>

"text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
20</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;" />
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU21" id=
"_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU21"></a><font style=
"font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">For
the three and nine months ended March 31, 2018, the Company
incurred interest expense of approximately $</font><font style=
"font-family:Times New Roman;">&nbsp;</font><font style=
"font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">0.2
million and $0.4 million respectively</font><font style=
"font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">,
related to all outstanding debt instrument</font><font style=
"font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">s</font><font style="font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;During
the three and nine months ended March 31, 2017, the Company
recognized interest expense of approximately $0.1 million and $6.2
million, respectively, associated with its previously outstanding
Senior S</font><font style=
"font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">ecured
Notes Payable held by affiliates of MAST Capital that were retired
in October 2016.</font></p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
12. Income Tax</p>
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:6pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;color:#000000;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
As of March 31, 2018, the Company has net operating loss
(<font style="font-weight:bold;">NOL</font>) carryforwards for
federal and state income tax purposes of approximately $1.7 billion
and $217 million, respectively. The federal and state NOL
carryforwards will expire from 2018 through 2037.</p>
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;color:#000000;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
On December 22, 2017, the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act (<font style=
"font-weight:bold;">Tax Act</font>) was signed into
law.&nbsp;&nbsp;Among other changes is a reduction in the federal
corporate income tax rate from 35% to 21%, effective January 1,
2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company has provisionally revalued its
deferred tax assets as a result of the Tax Act.&nbsp;&nbsp;As the
Company has not yet finalized its calculation of its deferred tax
position as of the enactment date, the impact of the tax law change
has not been finalized as of March 31, 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on
the Company’s provisional estimate, the effect of the reduction in
the corporate income tax rate resulted in a reduction in deferred
tax assets of approximately $248 million and an off-setting
adjustment to the valuation allowance.&nbsp;&nbsp;As of March 31,
2018 and June 30, 2017, the Company had provided a full valuation
allowance for all of its federal and state deferred tax assets,
therefore the reduction in the federal deferred tax assets
resulting from the Tax Act had no effect on the Company’s
consolidated balance sheet or statements of operations as of, and
for the three and nine months ended March 31, 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Company did not record any adjustments to its revaluation in the
three months ending March 31, 2018.&nbsp; The Company’s revaluation
of its deferred tax assets is subject to further refinement as
additional information becomes available and further analysis is
completed.&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;color:#000000;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
For the three and nine months ended March 31, 2018, the Company has
recorded an income tax benefit of $0.2 million due to the income
tax benefit related to the reversal of our valuation allowance as a
result of deferred tax liabilities acquired as part of our March
2018 Real Estate Asset Acquisition that provided sources of taxable
income to recover our existing deferred tax assets (see Note 5 for
further discussion).&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
13. Subsequent Events</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
None.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
21</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;" />
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU22" id=
"_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU22"></a><a name=
"ITEM_2_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_ANALYSIS_F" id=
"ITEM_2_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_ANALYSIS_F"></a><font style=
"font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;"><a name="ITEM_2_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_ANALYSIS_F"
id="ITEM_2_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_ANALYSIS_F"></a>Item&nbsp;2.
Management’s Discussion and Analysis of</font> <font style=
"font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Financial Condition and Results of Operations.</font></p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Overview</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
We are a holding company seeking to acquire assets and businesses,
where our people and other assets provide a competitive
advantage.&nbsp;&nbsp;In our 2017 fiscal year, we started a new
business — investment management.&nbsp;&nbsp;In March 2018, we
started our real estate business through the acquisition of an
80.1% interest in two Class A office buildings situated on 17 acres
of land in Fort Myers, Florida.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
We currently manage Great Elm Capital Corp. (<font style=
"font-weight:bold;">GECC</font>), a business development company
(<font style="font-weight:bold;">BDC</font>) as defined under the
Investment Company Act of 1940, as amended.&nbsp;&nbsp;Through our
management of GECC, we earn management and administrative fees, and
have the opportunity to earn incentive fees based upon achieving
performance targets.&nbsp;&nbsp;We also own approximately 18% of
the outstanding shares of common stock of GECC, which generated
approximately $1.9 million in dividends and approximately $2.8
million of mark-to-market losses for the nine months ended March
31, 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to GECC, we also manage three
separate accounts for an institutional investor totaling
approximately $33 million (par value).</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
In March 2018, through its majority-owned subsidiary, Great Elm FM
Holdings Inc., the Company acquired an 80.1% interest in CRIC IT
Fort Myers LLC (<font style="font-weight:bold;">Property
Owner</font>).&nbsp;&nbsp;The Property Owner owns a fee simple
interest in two Class A office buildings (Gartner I and Gartner II)
totaling 257,000 square feet and situated on 17 acres of land in
Fort Myers, Florida (collectively, <font style=
"font-weight:bold;">Property</font>).&nbsp;&nbsp;The Property is
fully leased, on a triple net basis, to Gartner, Inc. (<font style=
"font-weight:bold;">Gartner</font>) until March 31, 2030, which may
be extended in accordance with the terms of the
lease.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Gartner I lease contains two five-year
extensions and the Gartner II lease contains three five-year
extensions. The lease term calls for Gartner to make base monthly
lease payments of approximately $0.4 million as calculated on a
straight line basis over the remaining expected lease
term.&nbsp;&nbsp;We estimate that such payments will generate $5.7
million of revenue and $0.2 million of net income over the first
year of the lease and $70 million of revenue and $5.4 million of
net income over the remaining non-cancellable lease
term.&nbsp;&nbsp;Including the tax benefit recognized in connection
with the transaction, we estimate that net income generated over
the first year of the lease and over the remaining non-cancellable
lease term to be $0.4 million and $5.5 million respectively.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:12pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:10pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
We continue to explore other opportunities in the investment
management and real estate sectors, as well as opportunities in
other areas that we believe provide attractive risk-adjusted
returns on invested capital.&nbsp;&nbsp;As of the date of this
report, we have not entered into any firm commitments to make
additional acquisitions or investments in any of these areas.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:12pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:10pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
As of March 31, 2018, we had $1.7 billion of net operating loss
(<font style="font-weight:bold;">NOL</font>) carryforwards for
Federal income tax purposes.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Critical Accounting Policies</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The discussion and analysis of our financial condition and results
of operations is based upon our consolidated financial statements,
which have been prepared in accordance with U.S. generally accepted
accounting principles (<font style=
"font-weight:bold;">GAAP</font>). The preparation of these
financial statements requires our management to make significant
estimates and judgments that affect the reported amounts of assets,
liabilities, revenues and expenses, and related disclosure of
contingent assets and liabilities. These items are monitored and
analyzed by our management for changes in facts and circumstances,
and material changes in these estimates could occur in the future.
During the period ended March 31, 2018, we did not make material
changes in our critical accounting policies or underlying
assumptions as disclosed in our Annual Report on Form 10-K for the
fiscal year ended June 30, 2017 as it relates to recurring
transactions.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The non-recurring transactions in the period ended March 31, 2018
requiring management judgment and estimation are as follows:</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Debt Modification<font style="font-style:normal;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;As
of June 30, 2017, our subsidiary GECC GP Corp. (</font><font style=
"font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;">GP Corp.</font><font style=
"font-style:normal;">) had issued a note payable that carried a
maximum payout obligation of approximately $10.8 million, exclusive
of interest (</font><font style=
"font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;">GP Corp.
Note</font><font style="font-style:normal;">).&nbsp;&nbsp;The
parties agreed to restate the GP Corp. Note payable to have a
principal obligation of $3.3 million, bearing interest at LIBOR
plus 3.0%.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result of the transaction, we recorded
the fair value of the note on our balance sheet, which approximated
the aggregate carrying amount.</font></p>
<p style=
"text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
22</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;" />
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;line-height:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU23" id=
"_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU23"></a><font style=
"font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">GP
Corp. Stock Subscription Agreement Modification.</font><font style=
"font-style:normal;">&nbsp;&nbsp;In September 2017, we eliminated
the vesting provisions and removed the call rights for the GP Corp.
stock owned by employees of the Company.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result of
the elimination, we recognized stock-based compensation expense of
$1.5 million in th</font><font style="font-style:normal;">e period
en</font><font style="font-style:normal;">ded March 31, 2018</font>
<font style="font-style:normal;">equal to the estimated fair value
of the non-controlling interest held by our employees in GP
Corp.</font></p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;line-height:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Real Estate Acquisition.<font style=
"font-style:normal;">&nbsp;&nbsp;In March 2018, through its
majority-owned subsidiary, Great Elm FM Holdings, the Company
acquired an 80.1% interest in CRIC IT Fort Myers LLC
(</font><font style="font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;">Property
Owner</font><font style="font-style:normal;">) and a 19.9% interest
was issued to the prior owner.&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:16pt;line-height:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Results of Operations</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;line-height:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The following discussion is reflective of our investment management
and real estate businesses that commenced operations in November
2016 and March 2018, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;Correspondingly, our
results of operations for the three and nine month periods ended
March 31, 2018 are not comparable to the same periods ended March
31, 2017.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:16pt;line-height:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Investment Management Business</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;line-height:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The key metrics of our investment management business are:</p>
<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style=
"border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:5.24%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style=

&nbsp;</p>
</td>
<td valign="top" style="width:5.24%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;line-height:10pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:'Times New Roman';">
<font style=

▪</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p style=

provides the basis on which our management fees and performance

</td>

<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style=
"border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>

23</p>

<p style=

(1)</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Garamond;font-size:8pt;">
<a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU24" id=

<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style=

<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style=

<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style=
"border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style=

</td>
<td valign="top">
<p style=

<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
See “Non-GAAP Measurements” below.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Investment Management Revenue&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<a name="_Hlk505241329" id="_Hlk505241329"></a>For the three months
ended March 31, 2018, we recognized $0.7 million of management
fees; $0.3 million in administration fees and a net ($1.8) million
of incentive fees.&nbsp;&nbsp;The ($1.8) million of incentive fees
includes $0.3 million of incentive fees recognized and the reversal
of $2.1 million of incentive fees earned by GECM under the
investment management agreement and recognized in revenue in prior
periods. Generally speaking, GECM earns 20% of GECC’s pre incentive
fee net investment income (<font style=
"font-weight:bold;">NII</font>) in excess of a 7% hurdle under its
investment management agreement with GECC.&nbsp; Payment of this
fee is also subject to a total return hurdle as set forth in the
investment management agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;To the extent that any
of such NII is composed of non-cash income, then payment of the
incentive fees owed to GECM in respect of such NII is deferred
until received by GECC in cash.&nbsp; &nbsp;GECC’s largest
investment, Avanti Communications Group plc (Avanti), has generated
significant non-cash income in the form of payment-in-kind (PIK)
interest. &nbsp;In connection with the recent restructuring of
Avanti completed on April 26, 2018, GECC’s investment in Avanti’s
third lien notes was converted into Avanti common equity. &nbsp;As
a result of this debt-for-equity conversion, we have determined
that the accrued incentives fees associated with such PIK interest
generated by the third lien notes cannot at this time be recognized
in revenue and must be reversed for prior periods.&nbsp;
Notwithstanding this reversal, such incentives fees remain payable
under the investment management agreement (subject to achievement
of the return hurdles) and will be recognized in revenue to the
extent a hypothetical sale of the new common equity at the market
price would result in gross proceeds to GECC in excess of its
initial cost basis in the third lien notes.&nbsp;&nbsp;We can make
no assurances that such incentive fees will ultimately be
recognized in revenue or as to the timing of any such
recognition.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
For the nine months ended March 31, 2018, we recognized $1.9
million of management fees; $0.9 million in administrative fees;
and a net $0.7 million of incentive fees. The decrease from the
three month period ended March 31, 2017 primarily resulted from the
reversal of prior period incentive fees, offset by an increase in
assets under management.&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase from the nine
months ended March 31, 2017 primarily resulting from an increase in
assets under management offset by the reversal of prior period
incentive fees. In addition, our investment management business
commenced in November 2016.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Our management fees earned fluctuate based on the fair value of the
assets that we manage, subject to provisions of the respective
investment management agreements.&nbsp;&nbsp;Incentive fees earned
on the performance of assets that we manage are recognized based on
investment performance during the period, subject to the
achievement of minimum return levels or high water marks, in
accordance with the terms of the respective investment management
agreements. &nbsp;We have estimated that our incentive fees earned
and due from GECC as of March 31, 2018 are fully
collectible.&nbsp;&nbsp;The investment management agreement with
GECC defers our right to collect these fees until certain
milestones are achieved and these incentive fees are not expected
to be collected within the next 12 months and are classified as
non-current in the accompanying consolidated balance
sheet.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Investment Management Costs and Expenses</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:6pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
During the three months ended March 31, 2018, our investment
management business’ costs primarily consisted of payroll and
related costs of $0.8 million; professional fees of approximately
$0.2 million; facilities and other administrative costs of $0.1
million; and the amortization of intangible assets totaling $0.1
million.&nbsp;&nbsp;During the nine months ended March 31, 2018,
our investment management business’ costs primarily consisted of
payroll and related costs of $5.3 million, of which approximately
$1.5 million related to modified and accelerated GP Corp.
stock-based compensation charges; professional fees of
approximately $0.7 million; facilities and other administrative
costs of $0.4 million; and the amortization of intangible assets
totaling $0.4 million.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
In addition to the operating costs, we recognized interest expense
of $0.04 million and $0.2 million for the three and nine months
ended March 31, 2018, respectively, related to the GP Corp.
Note.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
24</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;" />

"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">

<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:8pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Real Estate Revenue</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
For the three and nine months ended March 31, 2018, we recognized
$0.4 million of rental income in connection with our newly acquired
Class A office buildings in Fort Myers, Florida.&nbsp;&nbsp;We
commenced our real estate business in March 2018.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Real Estate Costs and Expenses</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
During the three and nine months ended March 31, 2018, our real
estate business’ costs primarily consisted of management fees and
state sales tax expense of $0.02 million; depreciation of $0.08
million and the amortization of intangible assets totaling $0.03
million</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
In addition to the operating costs, we recognized interest expense
of $0.16 million and $0.02 million in net amortization of discount
and premium for the three months ended March 31, 2018 related to
the Senior Note and Subordinated Note (each as defined herein; see 
“Note 11-Borrowings” in the “Notes to Condensed and Consolidated
Financial Statements (Unaudited).</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:8pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Operating Costs – General Corporate</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<div>
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="center"
style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=
"padding-left:0pt;padding-Right:0.75pt;padding-Top:0.75pt;width:69.48%; border-bottom:solid 0.75pt transparent;">
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
&nbsp;</p>

</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CFF0FC" style=

<p style=

&nbsp;</p>
</td>

<p style=

&nbsp;</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CFF0FC" style=

<p style=

&nbsp;</p>
</td>

General and administrative</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=
"padding-left:0pt;padding-Right:0.75pt;padding-Top:0.75pt;padding-Bottom:0pt;width:3.14%;">
<p style=

&nbsp;</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=

<p style=

$</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=

&nbsp;</p>
</td>

4,745</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=

&nbsp;</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=

<p style=

&nbsp;</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=
"padding-left:0pt;padding-Right:0.75pt;padding-Top:0.75pt;padding-Bottom:0pt;width:1.98%;">
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;color:#000000;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
$</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=
"padding-left:0pt;padding-Right:0.75pt;padding-Top:0.75pt;padding-Bottom:0pt;width:1%;white-space:nowrap;">

&nbsp;</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=

<p style=

2,677</p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" style=
"padding-left:0pt;padding-Right:0.75pt;padding-Top:0.75pt;padding-Bottom:0pt;width:1%;white-space:nowrap;">
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:0pt;;text-indent:0pt;;color:#000000;font-size:1pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
&nbsp;</p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
For the three and nine months ended March 31, 2018, we recognized
total general and administrative expenses of approximately $1.7
million and $4.7 million, respectively. Our general corporate
operating costs for each quarter primarily consist of professional
fees and payroll costs as we continue to diligence asset and
business acquisition opportunities.&nbsp;&nbsp;For the three and
nine months ended March 31, 2018, professional fees in relation to
the diligence of opportunities were $0.7 million and $0.7 million,
respectively.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
In the nine months ended March 31, 2017, GECC reimbursed us $3.0
million for costs incurred in connection with the formation of
GECC, its merger with Full Circle Capital Corporation and related
matters.&nbsp;&nbsp;The $3.0 million was expensed during the 12
months ended June 30, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;The formation cost
reimbursement is reflected as a reduction of our corporate
expenses.&nbsp;&nbsp;The formation cost reimbursement is the
primary difference between general and administrative expenses
incurred in the respective comparable periods.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
25</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;" />
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<a name="_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU26" id=
"_AEIOULastRenderedPageBreakAEIOU26"></a><font style=
"font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">Interest
Expense</font></p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
We incurred interest expense during the three and nine months ended
March 31, 2018 of approximately $0.2 million and $0.4 million,
respectively, from our outstanding Senior Note, Subordinated Note,
and GP Corp. Note.&nbsp;&nbsp;For the three months ended March 31,
2017 we incurred interest of approximately $0.1 million from the GP
Corp. Note.&nbsp;&nbsp;During the nine months ended March 31, 2017,
we incurred significant non-recurring interest expenses associated
with the retirement of our previously outstanding senior secured
notes in October 2016.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:18pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;font-family:Garamond;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Dividends</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:6pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:10pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
For the three and nine months ended March 31, 2018, we received
$0.5 million and $1.9 million of dividends, respectively, on our
investment in GECC.&nbsp; We record our pro rata share of such
distributions if, as and when declared by GECC’s board of
directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;GECC did not begin distributing its income
until December 2016.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:18pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;font-family:Garamond;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Unrealized Loss</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:6pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:10pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
We mark-to-market our investment in GECC by reference to the
closing price of GECC common stock on Nasdaq (an observable Level 1
valuation input). For the three and nine months ended March 31,
2018, we recognized $1.2 million and $2.8 million of unrealized
loss, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;We deconsolidated GECC in November
2016 and recognized a net unrealized loss for the period ended
March 31, 2017 of approximately $7.6 million.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Discontinued Operations</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
On April 6, 2016, we entered into a purchase and sale agreement
with Optis providing for the sale of the entities that conducted
our patent licensing business (the <font style=
"font-weight:bold;">Divestiture</font>).&nbsp;&nbsp;The Divestiture
was completed on June 30, 2016.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<a name="_Hlk492909674" id="_Hlk492909674"></a>In the Divestiture,
we received $34.2 million in gross cash proceeds, inclusive of
reimbursement of $4.2 million of agreed upon expenses, and may be
entitled to up to an additional $10 million cash payment on June
30, 2018. Optis has claimed that it has losses indemnifiable under
the purchase and sale agreement in excess of the $10 million
contractual payment due on June 30, 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result,
we have not recognized any portion of the $10 million in the
accompanying consolidated financial statements for the periods
presented. Activity related to our legacy patent business is
reflected in our financial statements as discontinued
operations.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
We incurred discontinued operating costs of approximately $0.2
million through the nine month period ended March&nbsp;31, 2018
related to the representations and warranties associated with the
disposal of our legacy patent licensing business.&nbsp;&nbsp;For
the nine months ended March 31, 2017, we recognized a net gain from
discontinued operations of approximately $2.3 million associated
with a one-time litigation settlement.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Income Taxes</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:6pt;text-indent:0%;font-size:10pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
As of March 31, 2018, we had approximately $1.7 billion of NOL
carryforwards, with the corresponding deferred tax asset fully
reserved for financial reporting purposes, applicable to future
Federal income tax, if incurred.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October&nbsp;17,
2017, our stockholders <font style="color:#000000;">extended the
transfer restriction in our certificate of incorporation to help
preserve tax benefits associated with our NOLs.&nbsp;&nbsp;In
January 2018, upon expiration of our current rights plan, a new
rights plan went into effect that will expire on January 29,
2028.</font></p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:12pt;text-indent:0%;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
On December 22, 2017, the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act (<font style=
"font-weight:bold;">Tax Act</font>) was signed into
law.&nbsp;&nbsp;Among other changes resulting from the Tax Act is a
reduction in the Federal corporate income tax rate from 35% to 21%,
effective January 1, 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company has provisionally
revalued its deferred tax assets as a result of the Tax
Act.&nbsp;&nbsp;As the Company has not yet finalized its
calculation of its deferred tax position as of the enactment date,
the impact of the tax law change has not been finalized as of March
31, 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on the Company’s provisional estimate,
the effect of the reduction in the corporate income tax rate was a
reduction in deferred tax assets of approximately $248 million with
an off-setting adjustment to the valuation allowance.&nbsp;&nbsp;As
of March 31, 2018 and June 30, 2017, the Company had provided a
full valuation allowance for all of its Federal and state deferred
tax assets, therefore the reduction in the Federal deferred tax
assets resulting from the Tax Act will have no effect on the
Company’s consolidated balance sheet or statement of operations as
of, and for the three and nine months ended March 31,
2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company did not record any adjustments to its
revaluation in the three months ending March 31, 2018.&nbsp; The
Company’s revaluation of its deferred tax asset is subject to
further refinement as additional information becomes available and
further analysis is completed.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:12pt;text-indent:0%;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The Company does not believe the other changes resulting from the
Tax Act will have a material effect on its current financial
position or operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
26</p>
<hr style="page-break-after:always;width:100%;" />
<p style=
"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:12pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:1pt;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;color:#000000;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
For the three and nine months ended March 31, 2018, the Company has
recorded an income tax benefit of $0.2 million due to the income
tax benefit related to the reversal of our valuation allowance as a
result of deferred tax liabilities acquired as part of our March
2018 Real Estate Asset Acquisition that provided additional sources
of taxable income to recover our existing deferred tax assets (see
Note 5 for further discussion).&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Non-GAAP Measurements</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
The SEC has adopted rules to regulate the use in filings with the
SEC, and in public disclosures, of financial measures that are not
in accordance with US GAAP, such as EBITDA and adjusted EBITDA,
omission of non-recurring or infrequent items, and other omissions
of non-cash items whether recurring or non-recurring. These
measures are derived from methodologies other than in accordance
with US GAAP.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
We believe that <font style="font-weight:bold;">EBITDA</font>, the
non-cash adjustments listed below and adjusted EBITDA, are
important measures in addition to US GAAP segment results to be
used in evaluating our businesses. In addition, our management
reviews EBITDA and adjusted EBITDA as they evaluate acquisition
opportunities.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
These Non-GAAP measurements have limitations as an analytical tool,
and you should not consider these omissions either in isolation or
as a substitute for analyzing our results as reported under US
GAAP. Some of these limitations are:</p>
<div align="left">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style=

&nbsp;</p>
</td>
<td valign="top" style="width:5.24%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style=

<font style=
"font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
▪</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">

this measure does not reflect changes in, or cash requirements for,
our working capital needs;</p>

</div>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
For the periods presented, the following tables present our EBITDA
and adjusted EBITDA used in evaluating the results of our
operations and for the allocation of resources.</p>

&nbsp;</p>

"border-collapse:collapse; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td valign="top" style="width:7.69%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Garamond;font-size:8pt;">
&nbsp;</p>

<td valign="top" style="width:3.85%;white-space:nowrap">
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-size:8pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
<font style=
"font-size:8pt;font-family:Garamond;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
(1)</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;font-family:Garamond;font-size:8pt;">
Amount represents $2.7 million of unrecognized incentive fees
earned, net of $0.8 million of unrecognized related bonus
compensation expense.</p>

<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Liquidity and Capital Resources</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Cash Flows</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Operating cash flows used in continuing operations for the period
ended March 31, 2018 totaled approximately $3.1
million.&nbsp;&nbsp;The cash used in our continuing operations was
primarily the result of increases in receivables from our
investment management fees and other related party receivables of
$0.9 million and the funding of our operating
expenses.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Our investing activities primarily consisted of the $2.1 million
cash payment (net of cash and restricted cash acquired of $0.6
million) used in acquiring our initial real estate
assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
During the nine months ended March 31, 2018, outstanding warrants
were exercised resulting in the receipt of cash proceeds of
approximately $4.6 million and the issuance of 1,266,000 shares of
our common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, we made the first
payment due on our Senior Note payable related to our real estate
business of approximately $0.2 million.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-weight:bold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
Financial Condition</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
As of March 31, 2018, we had an unrestricted cash balance of $44.3
million.&nbsp;&nbsp;We also own 1,966,667 shares of GECC common
stock with an estimated fair value of $18.1 million as of March 31,
2018.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
We intend to make acquisitions or investments that will likely
result in the investment of all of our liquid financial resources,
issuance of equity securities and incurring
indebtedness.&nbsp;&nbsp;If we are unsuccessful at raising
additional capital resources, through either debt or equity, it is
unlikely we will be able execute our strategic growth
plan.&nbsp;&nbsp; See “Risk Factors”.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:center;margin-top:12pt;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
28</p>

<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
As of March 31, 2018, we had a related party GP Corp. Note due to
MAST Capital totaling $3.3 million that accrues interest at a
variable rate of LIBOR plus 3.0%, as adjusted for each 90-day
period (at March 31, 2018 the effective rate was 5.3%) through
maturity on November 3, 2026.&nbsp;&nbsp;The GP Corp. Note requires
minimum annual principal payments of $0.08 million and quarterly
interest-only payments.&nbsp;&nbsp;The GP Corp. Note is secured by
the profit sharing agreement between GECM and GP Corp. that
transfers profits generated by our management of GECC, with no
recourse to any of our other assets, entities or operations.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
As of March 31, 2018, we had a Senior Note due to Wells Fargo Bank
Northwest, National totaling $54.6 million that accrues interest at
a rate of 3.49% through maturity on March 15, 2030.&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Senior Note requires monthly principal and interest
payments.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Senior Note is secured by a first lien
mortgage on the Property and an Assignment of Leases and Rents,
with no recourse to any of our assets, entities or operations.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Garamond;font-size:10pt;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;text-transform:none;font-variant: normal;">
As of March 31, 2018, we had a Subordinated Note due to Wells Fargo
Bank Northwest, National totaling $2.7 million that accrues
interest at a rate of 15.0% through maturity on March 15,
2030.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Subordinated Note is a capital appreciation
note, whereby the monthly interest is capitalized to the principal
balance and due at maturity.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Subordinated Note is
secured by a second lien mortgage on the Property, and an
Assignment of Leases and Rents, with no recourse to any of our
assets, entities or operations.</p>
<p style=
"text-align:justify;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;text-indent:0%;font-family:Times New Roman;">
